Preparation (3 points total)¶

[1.5 points]¶

Choose and explain what metric(s) you will use to evaluate your algorithm’s performance. You should give a detailed argument for why this (these) metric(s) are appropriate on your data. That is, why is the metric appropriate for the task (e.g., in terms of the business case for the task). Please note: rarely is accuracy the best evaluation metric to use. Think deeply about an appropriate measure of performance.

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/gpiosenka/cards-image-datasetclassification We chose the playing cards dataset. The main use case is so that someone who is visually impaired can use this model to play with a regular deck of cards. Brail marked cards exist, but are not widely avialble. And deploying this model in a discrete app that plays the card name in the headphones of the user, can make the game playable for someone that is visually impaired.

Because of this use case, accuracy is the best metric to be used to evaulate this model. Accuracy helps ensure the correct identification of each card within the fixed number of classes [52].

[1.5 points]¶

Choose the method you will use for dividing your data into training and testing (i.e., are you using Stratified 10-fold cross validation? Shuffle splits? Why?). Explain why your chosen method is appropriate or use more than one method as appropriate. Convince me that your cross validation method is a realistic mirroring of how an algorithm would be used in practice. appropriate measure of performance.

In this particular use case, we are using a dataset that is pre-divided. The reasons for choosing to use the provided split is:

  1. This ensures that we are minimizing leakage that may be introduced if we split ourselves
  2. Given the high rating of the dataset on kaggle, we assume there it also has a good balance in the split for train and test with good spread of each of the classes.
  3. Using pre-split data helps us reduce errors on our end and saves us time in the process.

import ipywidgets as widgets
import random

def display_random_image(dataset):
    # Randomly select a batch
    batch = next(iter(dataset))

    # Randomly select an image from the batch
    random_index = random.randint(0, len(batch[0]) - 1)
    image, label = batch[0][random_index], batch[1][random_index]
    
    # Display the image
    plt.imshow(image.numpy().astype("uint8"))
    plt.title("Class: " + str(dataset.class_names[label]))
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

# Create a button widget
button = widgets.Button(description="Show Random Image")

# Display the button and the first random image
display_random_image(train_ds)  # Display an image initially

def count_images_per_class(dataset, class_names):
    class_counts = {name: 0 for name in class_names}
    for images, labels in dataset:
        for label in labels:
            class_name = class_names[label]
            class_counts[class_name] += 1
    return class_counts

# Count and display the number of images per class
train_class_counts = count_images_per_class(train_ds, class_Names)
print("Number of images per class in training dataset:")
for class_name, count in train_class_counts.items():
    print(f"{class_name}: {count}")

Because each of the classes have roughly the same number of images, we do not need to balance the dataset¶

We have applied a few augmentations to our images.¶

Variability of cards positioning relative to capturing device¶

  1. RandomFlip("vertical"),
  2. RandomRotation(0.1),

Cards can be placed or held in any orientation during gameplay.

Flipping vertically and rotating them simulates this variability, helping the model account for cards that may be encountered within the randomness of the real environment. The candidate using this model are also visually impaired, hence they may not detect these kind of variabilities when given a card, hence our model should account for it.

Variability of lighting conditions in different environments¶

  1. RandomBrightness(factor=0.1, value_range=(0.0, 1.0)),
  2. RandomContrast(0.1): The player may play these games in the bright lights of a casino or the backroom of a store, adjusting the brightness account for the variations in lighting conditions that may be encountered while playing. The contrast change accounts for similar variances along with different cards may also have different matte or clear finishes. Training our model for these kind of differences will help us when the conditions are not exactly ideal for capturing the card image.

# First Convolutional Layer (reduced filters)
cnn.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(pixels, pixels, 3)))

# First Pooling Layer
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Second Convolutional Layer (reduced filters)
cnn.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))

# Second Pooling Layer
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Dropout for Regularization (simplified)
cnn.add(Dropout(0.5))

# Flatten the output
cnn.add(Flatten())

# Simplified Dense Layer
cnn.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# Output Layer (remains the same)
cnn.add(Dense(len(class_Names), activation='softmax'))



learning_rate = 0.00015  # A lower learning rate

# Create the model
cnn = Sequential()

# # Simplified Data Augmentation
cnn.add(RandomFlip("horizontal"))  # flip horizontally
cnn.add(RandomRotation(0.01))       # rotate by 5%
cnn.add( RandomBrightness(factor=0.05, value_range=(0.0, 1.0))) # add some to the mean
cnn.add( RandomContrast(0.05)) # add or decrease contrast

# First Convolutional Layer (reduced filters)
cnn.add(Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(pixels, pixels, 3)))

# First Pooling Layer
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Second Convolutional Layer (reduced filters)
cnn.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))

# Third Convolutional Layer (reduced filters)
cnn.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))

# Second Pooling Layer
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Dropout for Regularization (simplified)
cnn.add(Dropout(0.5))

# Flatten the output
cnn.add(Flatten())

# Simplified Dense Layer
cnn.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# Output Layer (remains the same)
cnn.add(Dense(len(class_Names), activation='softmax'))

optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)

cnn.compile(optimizer=optimizer, 
            loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', 
            metrics=['accuracy'])

Adding all the augmentations actually made the loss increase exponentially on the validation data. and the new layer did not increase the accuracy from the previous one. For the next one, We will just add one augmentation, and changing the layers on the convolution layers (128, 64, 32 in all of them)¶

In [27]:
# Create the model
cnn = Sequential()

# # Simplified Data Augmentation
# cnn.add(RandomFlip("horizontal"))  # flip horizontally
cnn.add(RandomRotation(0.01))       # rotate by 5%
# cnn.add( RandomBrightness(factor=0.05, value_range=(0.0, 1.0))) # add some to the mean
# cnn.add( RandomContrast(0.05)) # add or decrease contrast

# First Convolutional Layer (reduced filters)
cnn.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(pixels, pixels, 3)))

# First Pooling Layer
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Second Convolutional Layer (reduced filters)
cnn.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))

# Second Pooling Layer
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Third Convolutional Layer (reduced filters)
cnn.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))

# Third Pooling Layer
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Dropout for Regularization (simplified)
cnn.add(Dropout(0.35))

# Flatten the output
cnn.add(Flatten())

# Simplified Dense Layer
cnn.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# Output Layer (remains the same)
cnn.add(Dense(len(class_Names), activation='softmax'))

learning_rate = 0.00001  # A lower learning rate

optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)

cnn.compile(optimizer=optimizer, 
            loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', 
            metrics=['accuracy'])

The accuracy has been increased slightly but the loss function is now increasing instead of decreasing. This could mean exploding gradients, we will reduce the number of layers to 2 and run it without the data augmentation. Also added a stop loss function so that it stops when loss is minimized.¶

In [31]:
cnn = Sequential()

# Enhanced Data Augmentation
# cnn.add(RandomFlip("horizontal"))
# cnn.add(RandomRotation(0.1))  # increased to 10%
# cnn.add(RandomTranslation(height_factor=0.1, width_factor=0.1))  # increased to 10%
# cnn.add(RandomBrightness(factor=0.1))
# cnn.add(RandomContrast(0.1))
# cnn.add(RandomZoom(0.1))

# First Convolutional Layer (with L2 Regularization)
cnn.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(pixels, pixels, 3), kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))
cnn.add(BatchNormalization())
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Second Convolutional Layer
cnn.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))
cnn.add(BatchNormalization())
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Dropout for Regularization
cnn.add(Dropout(0.5))  # increased to 50%

# Flatten the output
cnn.add(Flatten())

# Dense Layer with L2 Regularization
cnn.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))

# Output Layer
cnn.add(Dense(len(class_Names), activation='softmax'))

optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)

# Compile the model
cnn.compile(optimizer=optimizer, 
            loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', 
            metrics=['accuracy'])

from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

# Configure the EarlyStopping callback
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_loss',
    min_delta=0.001,  # minimium amount of change to count as an improvement
    patience=10,      # how many epochs to wait before stopping
    restore_best_weights=True,  # restore model weights from the epoch with the best value of the monitored quantity
    verbose=1
)

history_4 = cnn.fit(train_ds, validation_data=valid_ds, epochs=20, callbacks=[early_stopping])
cnn_4 = cnn

In [38]:
cnn = Sequential()

# First Convolutional Layer (with L2 Regularization)
cnn.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(pixels, pixels, 3), kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))
cnn.add(BatchNormalization())
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Second Convolutional Layer
cnn.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))
cnn.add(BatchNormalization())
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

#third conv layer
cnn.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))
cnn.add(BatchNormalization())
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(2, 2))

# Dropout for Regularization
cnn.add(Dropout(0.5))  # increased to 50%

# Flatten the output
cnn.add(Flatten())

# Dense Layer with L2 Regularization
cnn.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))

# Output Layer
cnn.add(Dense(len(class_Names), activation='softmax'))

optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)

# Compile the model
cnn.compile(optimizer=optimizer, 
            loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', 
            metrics=['accuracy'])

history_6 = cnn.fit(train_ds, validation_data=valid_ds, epochs=30)
cnn_6 = cnn

predictions1 = np.load('predictions1.npy')
predictions2 = np.load('predictions2.npy')
predictions3 = np.load('predictions3.npy')
predictions4 = np.load('predictions4.npy')

predictions1 = np.argmax(predictions1, axis=1)
predictions2 = np.argmax(predictions2, axis=1)
predictions3 = np.argmax(predictions3, axis=1)
predictions4 = np.argmax(predictions4, axis=1)

# Assuming test_ds has the labels in the same order
true_labels = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_ds], axis=0)
# true_labels = np.array([label for _, label in test_ds.unbatch()])

def mcnemars_test(observed):
    b, c = observed[0, 1], observed[1, 0]
    chi_squared = (abs(b - c) - 1) ** 2 / (b + c) if b + c > 0 else 0
    p_value = 1 - np.math.erf(chi_squared / np.sqrt(2))
    return chi_squared, p_value

def create_contingency_table(preds1, preds2, true_labels):
    tb = np.zeros((2, 2), dtype=int)
    for pred1, pred2, true in zip(preds1, preds2, true_labels):
        tb[int(pred1 == true), int(pred2 == true)] += 1
    return tb

# Compare each pair of predictions
model_predictions = [predictions1, predictions2, predictions3, predictions4]
model_names = ["Model 4", "Model 5", "Model 6", "Model 7"]

for i in range(len(model_predictions)):
    for j in range(i + 1, len(model_predictions)):
        observed = create_contingency_table(model_predictions[i], model_predictions[j], true_labels)
        chi_squared, p_value = mcnemars_test(observed)
        print(f"McNemar's test for {model_names[i]} vs {model_names[j]}: Chi-Squared={chi_squared}, P-Value={p_value}")

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc, roc_auc_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import label_binarize

predictions1 = np.load('predictions1.npy')
predictions2 = np.load('predictions2.npy')
predictions3 = np.load('predictions3.npy')
predictions4 = np.load('predictions4.npy')
 
probabilities_mlp = mlp.predict(test_ds)

num_classes = 53  
binarized_labels = label_binarize(true_labels, classes=range(num_classes))

def calculate_micro_average_roc(probabilities, binarized_labels):
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(binarized_labels.ravel(), probabilities.ravel())
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    return fpr, tpr, roc_auc

# Calculate micro-average ROC and AUC for each model
fpr_mlp, tpr_mlp, roc_auc_mlp = calculate_micro_average_roc(probabilities_mlp, binarized_labels)
fpr_cnn4, tpr_cnn4, roc_auc_cnn4 = calculate_micro_average_roc(predictions1, binarized_labels)
fpr_cnn5, tpr_cnn5, roc_auc_cnn5 = calculate_micro_average_roc(predictions2, binarized_labels)
fpr_cnn6, tpr_cnn6, roc_auc_cnn6 = calculate_micro_average_roc(predictions3, binarized_labels)
fpr_cnn7, tpr_cnn7, roc_auc_cnn7 = calculate_micro_average_roc(predictions4, binarized_labels)

# Plotting the micro-average ROC curves
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.plot(fpr_mlp, tpr_mlp, label=f'MLP (AUC = {roc_auc_mlp:.2f})', color='navy')
plt.plot(fpr_cnn4, tpr_cnn4, label=f'Model 4 (AUC = {roc_auc_cnn4:.2f})')
plt.plot(fpr_cnn5, tpr_cnn5, label=f'Model 5 (AUC = {roc_auc_cnn5:.2f})')
plt.plot(fpr_cnn6, tpr_cnn6, label=f'Model 6 (AUC = {roc_auc_cnn6:.2f})')
plt.plot(fpr_cnn7, tpr_cnn7, label=f'Model 7 (AUC = {roc_auc_cnn7:.2f})')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Micro-average ROC Curves for MLP and CNN Models')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

# Load ResNet50 without the top classification layer
resnet_base = ResNet50(weights='imagenet', include_top=False)

# Freeze the layers of ResNet50
for layer in resnet_base.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

NUM_CLASSES = 53 

# Create the model
input_x = Input(shape=(pixels, pixels, 3))

# Use ResNet as the base
base_output = resnet_base(input_x)
x = Flatten()(base_output)

# Add the custom layers on top
x = Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(x)
predictions = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='softmax', kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform')(x)

model = Model(inputs=input_x, outputs=predictions)

model.summary()

# Load your datasets
train_ds = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(
    "cards/train",
    batch_size=32,
    image_size=(128, 128),  # Ensure this matches your expected input size
    seed=0
)

test_ds = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(
    "cards/test",
    batch_size=32,
    image_size=(128, 128),  # Ensure this matches your expected input size
    seed=0
)

# Compile the model
opt = Adam()
model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss=sparse_categorical_crossentropy, metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model
num_epochs = 30

for e in range(num_epochs):
    for images, labels in train_ds:
        images = preprocess_input(images)  # Preprocess the images
        loss, _ = model.train_on_batch(images, labels)  # Train the model on the batch
    print(f'Finished epoch {e}, loss: {loss}')

# Evaluate the model
num_points = 0
num_correct = 0

for images, labels in test_ds:
    images = preprocess_input(images)
    yhat = model.predict(images)
    yhat = np.argmax(yhat, axis=1)

    num_points += len(labels)
    num_correct += sum(yhat == labels.numpy())

accuracy = num_correct / num_points
print(f'Test Accuracy: {accuracy}')

# Load the predictions from Model 4
predictions_model4 = np.load('predictions4.npy')
predictions_model4 = np.argmax(predictions_model4, axis=1)

# Get predictions from the new ResNet50-based model
predictions_resnet = []
for images, _ in test_ds:
    images = preprocess_input(images)
    preds = model.predict(images)
    preds = np.argmax(preds, axis=1)
    predictions_resnet.extend(preds)

predictions_resnet = np.array(predictions_resnet)

true_labels = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_ds], axis=0)

# McNemar's test function
def mcnemars_test(observed):
    b, c = observed[0, 1], observed[1, 0]
    chi_squared = (abs(b - c) - 1) ** 2 / (b + c) if b + c > 0 else 0
    p_value = 1 - np.math.erf(chi_squared / np.sqrt(2))
    return chi_squared, p_value

def create_contingency_table(preds1, preds2, true_labels):
    tb = np.zeros((2, 2), dtype=int)
    for pred1, pred2, true in zip(preds1, preds2, true_labels):
        tb[int(pred1 == true), int(pred2 == true)] += 1
    return tb

# Create the contingency table for the ResNet model and Model 4
observed = create_contingency_table(predictions_model4, predictions_resnet, true_labels)
chi_squared, p_value = mcnemars_test(observed)
print(f"McNemar's test for ResNet Model vs Model 4: Chi-Squared={chi_squared}, P-Value={p_value}")
